From April 3, 2020 0:00 JST until the end of April, "all efficacy of single or multiple-entry visa issued by April 2, 2020 at Japanese Embassies or Consulates General" in the following countries “are terminated and visa exemption measures are suspended”:
- Asia: Indonesia, South Korea, Singapore, Thailand, Taiwan, China (including Hong Kong and Macau), Philippines, Brunei, Vietnam, Malaysia;
- Oceania: Australia, New Zealand;
- North America: Canada, United States of America;
- South America: Ecuador, Chile, Dominica, Panama, Brazil, Bolivia;
- Europe: Albania, Armenia, United Kingdom, North Macedonia, Cyprus, Greece, Croatia, Kosovo, Slovakia, Serbia, Czech Republic, Hungary, Finland, Bulgaria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Poland, Moldova, Montenegro, Latvia, Lithuania, and Romania;
- Middle East: Israel, Egypt, Turkey, Bahrain;
- Africa: Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ivory Coast, Morocco, Mauritius.
"When entering Japan, the affected individual will need to apply for a new visa."

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan (MOFA) issued a "Travel advice and Warning on Infectious Diseases Level 3: Avoid All Travel" for the following countries on April 24, 2020:
- (Latin America) Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Dominican Republic, Barbados, Peru;
- (Europe) Ukraine, Belarus, Russia;
- (Middle East) United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia;
- (Africa) Djibouti.

From April 29, 2020 0:00 JST "until further notice, entry to Japan will be denied to foreigners who have visited" the following countries "within 14 days prior to the application for landing", in accordance with Article 5, Paragraph (1), Item (xiv) of the Immigration Control and Refugee Recognition Act, "unless exceptional circumstances are found":
- Central / South America: Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Dominican Republic, Barbados, Peru;
- Europe: Ukraine, Belarus, Russia;
- Middle East: United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia;
- Africa: Djibouti.
"Japanese nationals are exempted." "[F]oreigners with the status of residence of "Permanent Resident", "Spouse or Child of Japanese National", "Spouse or Child of Permanent Resident" or "Long Term Resident" are treated in principle as persons in special circumstances, enabling them to enter Japan." Therefore, "[f]oreigners with the aforementioned status of residence who had departed Japan with Re-entry Permission between April 3 and April 28, 2020, and then have stayed only in the 14 countries newly added to the entry-ban measures on April 29."

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan (MOFA) issued a "Travel advice and Warning on Infectious Diseases Level 3: Avoid All Travel" for the following countries on May 12, 2020:
- (Asia) Maldives;
- (Central and South America) Uruguay, Colombia, the Bahamas, Honduras, Mexico;
- (Europe) Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan;
- (Africa) Cape Verde, Gabon, Guinea-Bissau, São Tomé and Príncipe, Equatorial Guinea.
[Comment: countries have been assigned to a continent, in that precise order, according to MOFA’s notice.]

From May 16, 2020 0:00 JST "until further notice, entry to Japan will be denied to foreigners who have visited" the following countries "within 14 days prior to the application for landing", in accordance with Article 5, Paragraph (1), Item (xiv) of the Immigration Control and Refugee Recognition Act, "unless exceptional circumstances are found":
- Central Asia: Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan;
- Asia: Maldives;
- Central/South America: Uruguay, Colombia, Bahamas, Honduras, Mexico;
- Africa: Cabo Verde, Gabon, Guinea-Bissau, São Tomé und Príncipe, Equatorial Guinea.
"Japanese nationals are exempted." “[F]oreigners with the status of residence of “Permanent Resident”, “Spouse or Child of Japanese National”, “Spouse or Child of Permanent Resident” or “Long Term Resident” are treated in principle as persons in special circumstances, enabling them to enter Japan.” Therefore, “[f]oreigners with the aforementioned status of residence who had departed from Japan with Re-entry Permission between April 29 and May 15, 2020, and then have stayed only in the aforementioned 13 countries newly added to the entry-ban measures on May 14, are treated in principle as persons in special circumstances. Please note that foreigners who had left Japan during the said period with a re-entry permission, and then have also visited the remaining 87 countries and regions on top of the 13 countries newly added to the entry-ban measures on May 14 are in principle subject to entry bans.”

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan (MOFA) issued a "Travel advice and Warning on Infectious Diseases Level 3: Avoid All Travel" for the following countries on May 22, 2020:
- (Asia) India, Pakistan, Bangladesh;
- (Latin America) Argentina, El Salvador;
- (Europe) Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan;
- (Middle East / Africa) Afghanistan, Ghana, Guinea, South Africa.
[Comment: countries have been assigned to a continent, in that precise order, according to MOFA’s notice.]

From May 27, 2020 0:00 JST "until further notice, entry to Japan will be denied to foreigners who have visited" the following countries "within 14 days prior to the application for landing", in accordance with Article 5, Paragraph (1), Item (xiv) of the Immigration Control and Refugee Recognition Act, "unless exceptional circumstances are found":
- Middle East: Afghanistan;
- Central/South America: Argentina, El Salvador
- Asia: Bangladesh, India, Pakistan;
- Africa: Ghana, Guinea, South Africa;
- Europe: Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan.
"Japanese nationals and "Special Permanent Residents" are exempted." "Foreigners with the aforementioned status of residence who had departed from Japan with Re-entry Permission between May 16 and May 26, 2020, and then have stayed only in the aforementioned 11 countries newly added to the entry-ban measures on May 27, are treated in principle as persons in special circumstances. Please note that foreigners who had left Japan during the said period with a re-entry permission, and then have also visited the remaining 100 countries and regions on top of the 11 countries newly added to the entry-ban measures on May 27 are in principle subject to entry bans. Foreigners with the aforementioned status of residence who had departed Japan with re-entry permission on or after May 27 in principle will NOT be treated as persons in special circumstances and be subject to entry-bans."
[Comment: region assignment according to MOFA]

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan (MOFA) issued a "Travel advice and Warning on Infectious Diseases Level 3: Avoid All Travel" for the following countries on June 5, 2020:
- (Latin America) Guyana, Cuba, Guatemala, Grenada, Costa Rica, Jamaica, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Nicaragua, Haiti;
- (Europe/Central Asia) Georgia;
- (Middle East/Africa) Algeria, Iraq, Eswatini, Cameroon, Senegal, Central African Republic, Mauritania, Lebanon.
[Comment: countries have been assigned to a continent or region, in that precise order, according to MOFA’s notice.]

